\section{Time-Frequency Signal Analysis using Short Time Fourier Transform}\label{sec:t_f_stft}

A time domain signal can be equivalently represented in the
frequency domain. While there is an equivalence between the signal
representations in these two domains, the signal in one domain does
not explicitly convey information about the localized contents in the other domain.
Time-frequency signal processing deals with the analysis and
processing of signals in a joint time-frequency domain.
%
\subsection{Short-Time Fourier Transform~(STFT)}

The short-time Fourier transform~(STFT) is a powerful tool which is
widely used in time-frequency analysis to investigate  time
localized
spectral characteristics of a signal~\cite{Cohen:1989,Cohen:1995}. %The STFT of the signal
%reflects the frequency characteristic as a function of time.
In order to study the time domain signal $f$ in the vicinity of time
$t$ in frequency domain, a window function is used and Fourier
analysis is performed. The STFT is given by
%the signal is localized at time $t$ using the
%window function and then the Fourier analysis is performed. For a
%window function $h(t)$, STFT $\stftf(t,\omega)$ of signal $f(t)$ is
%defined as
\begin{align}\label{Eq:stft_tf_def}
\stftf(t,\omega) = \int f(\tau)\,{h(t -\tau)}\, e^{-i \omega
\tau}\,d\tau,
\end{align}
%
where a time-shift of the window function, $h$, provides the
localization in time. Hence, the time-frequency distribution using
the STFT is the collection of Fourier transforms of the windowed
signal about all points of translation $t$.  For brevity, the
notation for the STFT, $\stftf(t,\omega)$ in \eqref{Eq:stft_tf_def},
suppresses the dependence on $h$.

The effectiveness of the STFT in \eqref{Eq:stft_tf_def} for various
applications is sensitive to the selection of window function
$h$~\cite{Cohen:1995,Czerwinski:1997,Zhong:2010}. The basic problem
in window selection is the trade-off between a greater window width
for better frequency resolution and a lesser window width for
capturing the localized temporal properties of the signal~\cite{Czerwinski:1997}. %A window
%function with greater/lesser width in the time domain produces greater/lesser
%resolution in the frequency domain. %because of spectral smoothing,
%whereas a lesser width window fails to capture the localized
%contents in the frequency domain.

\subsection{Signal Inversion from STFT Distribution}

The STFT representation of the signal in \eqref{Eq:stft_tf_def}
belongs to the class of linear representations which satisfy simple
reconstruction properties~\cite{Cohen:1989,Cohen:1995}. %The marginal of the
%distribution in one domain can be obtained by integrating out the
%other domain.
The signal $f(t)$ can be recovered from its STFT representation
$\stftf(t,\omega)$, up to a constant factor, through the weighted
marginal
%
\begin{align}\label{Eq:stft_tf_inversion_1}
\int \stftf(t,\omega)\, e^{i\omega t}\,d\omega = C_1\, f(t)
\end{align}
%
and the Fourier transform $F(\omega)$ of the signal $f(t)$ can be
obtained from $\stftf(t,\omega)$ as frequency marginal which is
obtained by integrating out the time variable as
%
\begin{align}\label{Eq:stft_tf_inversion_2}
\int \stftf(t,\omega)\,dt = C_2\, F(\omega),
\end{align}
%
where $C_1$ and $C_2$ are constants which depend upon the window
function.


\subsection{Characteristic Function for STFT Distribution}

The characteristic function has been widely used to study the
localized characteristics of time-frequency
distributions~\cite{Cohen:1989,Cohen:1995}. The characteristic
function $M(\varsigma,\tau)$ for the STFT representation
$\stftf(t,\omega)$ is defined as~\cite{Cohen:1989}
%
\begin{align}\label{Eq:Ch_tf_def}
M(\varsigma, \tau) = \iint \big|\stftf(t,\omega)\big|^2 \, e^{i
\varsigma t} \, e^{i \tau \omega}\, dt\,d\omega.
\end{align}
%
We can see that the characteristic function $M(\varsigma,\tau)$ is a
transformed distribution which is equivalent to the two dimensional
inverse Fourier transform of the squared magnitude of the STFT
distribution $\stftf(t,\omega)$ in \eqref{Eq:stft_tf_def}. We make it clear here that the we are interested in the STFT based time-frequency representation of a signal, whereas the term ``time-frequency distributions" in this thesis is used to represent large class of time-frequency representations of a signal~\cite{Cohen:1989,Cohen:1995}.

\section{Spatially Localized Spherical Harmonic Transform}\label{ch4:sec:SLSHT}

\subsection{Definition of SLSHT}
\label{sec:dfnslsht}

We define the SLSHT in analogy to the STFT in time-frequency
analysis. Judicious choices of rotations on the sphere serve as
counterparts of translations in \eqref{Eq:stft_tf_def} in the time
domain. We re-locate, through rotation, an azimuthally-symmetric
window function (centered at the north pole) to achieve localization
in the spatial domain. We first define the SLSHT and use it to
define the SLSHT distribution as spatio-spectral representation of
the signal.



\begin{definition}[Spatially Localized Spherical Harmonic Transform]
For a  signal \mbox{$f\in\lsph$}, define the directional SLSHT
 $g(\unit{y};{\ell},m) \in \lsph$ of
degree $\ell$ and order
  $m$ as the spherical harmonic transform of a localized signal where
  localization is provided by the rotation operator $\rotopz$ acting on azimuthally symmetric window function
  $h\in\lsph$, i.e.,
  %
\begin{align}
    \label{Eq:stft_spatial1}
        g(\unit{y};{\ell},m) = g(\unit{y};n) \dfn
        \intsph
        \parn[\big]{\rotopz h}(\unit{x})     &     f(\unit{x}) \conj{Y_{\ell}^m(\unit{x})}
         \,ds(\unit{x}), \nonumber \\ &\unit{y} = \unit{y}(\vartheta,\varphi), \,
        (\ell,m)\leftrightarrow n.
\end{align}
\end{definition}

The SLSHT is dependent on the chosen window $h$, but for brevity,
this dependence is not explicit in the notation. We emphasize that, unlike the spherical harmonic coefficient of the signal $f$,
$\shc{f}{\ell}{m}$, which is only a function of degree $\ell$ and
order $m$, the SLSHT provides a spatially-varying spherical harmonic
representation of the signal (i.e., $g(\unit{y};{\ell},m)$ is a
function of the spatial localization $\unit{y}$ and degree and
order). We call $g(\unit{y};{\ell},m)$ the SLSHT of degree $\ell$ and
order $m$.

\subsection{SLSHT Harmonic Expansion}
Here, we express the relation between the SLSHT
$g(\unit{y};{\ell},m)$ and the spherical harmonic coefficients of
the signal $f$. First we determine the spherical harmonic
coefficients corresponding to the rotated window. We are interested
in the case where both the signal $f(\unit{x})$ and the window kernel
$h(\unit{x})$ are band-limited. Let us assume that $f(\unit{x})\in
\lsphL{L_f}$ and  $h(\unit{x})\in \lsphL{L_h}$ (since the kernel is
assumed to be azimuthally symmetric, $h(\unit{x})\in \lsphL{L_h}^0
\subset \lsphz$ would be a more precise notation).


Specializing \eqref{eqn:rotation_symm} for the SLSHT window kernel
$h$ at point $\unit{x} = \unit{x}(\theta,\varphi)$, we define

\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:window_r}
    \shc{h}{r}{}(\unit{y}) \dfn \innerp[\big]{\rotopz h}{Y_r} =
    \sqrt{\frac{4\pi}{2p+1}}\conj{Y_p^q(\unit{y})} \shc{h}{p}{0}, \quad \unit{y}
    = \unit{y}(\vartheta,\varphi), \quad (p,q)\leftrightarrow r.
\end{equation}
%
%
Using \eqref{Eq:window_r}, \eqref{Eq:f_expansion}, \eqref{Eq:fcoeff} and the mapping $(s,t)\leftrightarrow u$, we can alternatively write $g(\unit{y};n)$ in \eqref{Eq:stft_spatial1} as %
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:stft_spectral}
    g(\unit{y};n) = \sum_{u=0}^{N_f}  \shc{f}{u}{} \sum_{r=0}^{N_h}
\shc{h}{r}{}(\unit{y})\,T(u;r;n),
\end{equation}
where $N_h=L_h^2+2L_h$ and
\begin{equation}
\label{Ch4:Eq:triple_prod_abc}
    T(u;r;n) = T(r;u;n) \dfn \intsph Y_r(\unit{x}) Y_u(\unit{x}) \conj{Y_n(\unit{x})} \,ds(\unit{x})
\end{equation}
denotes the spherical harmonic triple product, the explicit
expression of which is provided in \eqref{Eq:Def_triple_product}.

\begin{remark}
It is implicit in the formulation of SLSHT that the signal of
interest is band-limited to $L_f < \infty$. As a signal has finite
energy, its spherical harmonic Fourier coefficients are square
summable. Consequently, any signal can be arbitrarily closely
approximated by a band-limited signal by making $L_f$ sufficiently
large. The study of the involved approximation errors on the SLSHT
is outside the scope of this thesis.
\end{remark}

\begin{remark}
It is important to note here that each SLSHT component of the
form $g(\unit{y}; n)$ is a band-limited function on the sphere with
band-limit $L_h$, that is, $\innerp[\big]{g(\unit{y}; n)}{Y_r^s} = 0$
for all $r>L_h$.
\end{remark}

\subsection{SLSHT Distribution and Matrix Formulation}

\begin{definition}[SLSHT Distribution] The SLSHT distribution $\bv{g}(\unit{x})$ of a signal
$f\in\lsph$ is an indexed vector of all SLSHT components of the form
$g(\unit{y}; n)$ as defined in~(\ref{Eq:stft_spatial1}) for $n=0,
1,\cdots, N_g$, i.e.,
%
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:stft_matrix_def}
    \bv{g}(\unit{y})\dfn \parn[\big]{g(\unit{y};0), \, g(\unit{y};1),\, g(\unit{y};2),
        \, \cdots, \, g(\unit{y};N_g)}',
\end{equation}
where $N_g = L_g^2+2L_g$ and $L_g = L_f + L_h$.
%
\end{definition}

\begin{remark}
The SLSHT distribution is a generalization of the transform
in~\cite{Simons:1997} and provides the representation of a signal in the joint spatio-spectral domain.
\end{remark}

Using the preceding formulation, the SLSHT distribution
$\bv{g}(\unit{y})$ in~\eqref{Eq:stft_matrix_def} can be written in
matrix form as
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:stft_matrix}
    \bv{g}(\unit{y}) = \bv{\Psi}(\unit{y}) \bv{f},
\end{equation}
where $\bv{f} = \parn[\big]{\mathcal{F}f}(\unit{x})$ and $\bv{\Psi}$
is the transformation operator matrix of size $(N_g+1)\times
(N_f+1)$, which transforms the given signal in spectral domain to the
spatio-spectral domain and is given by
%
\begin{equation}\label{Eq:psi_matrix}
\bv{\Psi}(\unit{y}) = \left[ {\begin{array}{cccc}
  \psi_{0,0}(\unit{y})& \psi_{0,1}(\unit{y})& \cdots & \psi_{0,N_f}(\unit{y})  \\
  \psi_{1,0}(\unit{y})& \psi_{1,1}(\unit{y})& \cdots & \psi_{1,N_f}(\unit{y})  \\
 \vdots &\vdots &&\vdots  \\[-2mm]
 \psi_{N_g,0}(\unit{y})&\ \psi_{N_g,1}(\unit{y})& \cdots& \psi_{N_g,N_f}(\unit{y})  \\
 \end{array} } \right]
\end{equation}
%
with entries
%
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:kernel_element}
    \psi_{n,u}(\unit{y}) = \sum_{r=0}^{N_h} \shc{h}{r}{}(\unit{y})\,T(u;r;n).
\end{equation}


\begin{remark}
The matrix form in~(\ref{Eq:stft_matrix}) transforms the spectral
response of the signal $\bv{f}$ to the joint spatio-spectral domain.
The size of the transformation matrix is dependent on the spectral
bandwidth of the input signal $f$ and the window function $h$. The
value of matrix elements is dependent on the applied rotation
$\unit{y}$ and the window function $h$, whose choice will be
discussed in Section~\ref{ch4:sec:window}.
\end{remark}

\subsection{Inversion of Signal from its SLSHT distribution}
Recovery of the spectral components of the signal from its localized
transform was first shown in~\cite{Simons:1997}. For the sake of
completeness, based on our matrix formulation, and explicit
expression of the transform in terms of rotated window function, we
provide an alternative formulation. We present the result in the
following theorem.

%
\begin{theorem}[Inversion of Signal from SLSHT Distribution]
%\mathbf{(Inversion of Signal from SLSHT Distribution)}
\label{thm:inversion} If $\bv{g}(\unit{y})$ represents the SLSHT
distribution of the signal $f$ using an azimuthally symmetric window
function $h$, where the distribution is of the
form~(\ref{Eq:stft_matrix_def}), then the spectral domain response
$\bv{f}$ of $f$ can be recovered from $\bv{g}(\unit{y})$ up to a
multiplicative factor as the spherical harmonics marginal
$\unit{f}$, which is obtained by integrating the SLSHT distribution
over the spatial domain as
%
\begin{align}\label{Eq:invthm}
\unit{f}  =   \intsph \bv{g}(\unit{y}) \,ds(\unit{y})
 =  \sqrt{4\pi} \, \shc{h}{0}{0} \times \big(\,\shc{f}{0}{},\, \shc{f}{1}{},\, \cdots,\, \shc{f}{N_f}{},\, 0,\, \cdots,\,
 0\,\big)',
\end{align}
%
where $\unit{f}$ denotes the spherical harmonics marginal and is a
vector of length $N_g+1$ where only the first $N_f+1$ elements are
non-zero.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
Integrating~(\ref{Eq:stft_matrix}) over the spatial domain gives
%
\begin{align}\label{Eq:invstart}
\intsph\bv{g}(\unit{y})\,ds(\unit{y}) =
\big(\intsph\bv{\Psi}(\unit{y}) \,ds(\unit{y})\big)\,\bv{f}.
\end{align}
%
The integral of kernel matrix $\bv{\Psi}$ is obtained by integrating
each matrix element $\psi_{n,u}(\unit{y})$
in~(\ref{Eq:kernel_element}), that is,
%
\begin{align}\label{Eq:kernel_integral}
\psi_{n,u}(\unit{y})\,ds(\unit{y}) = \sum_{r=0}^{N_h} T(u;r;n)
\intsph \shc{h}{r}{}(\unit{y})\,ds(\unit{y})
\end{align}
%
Now, using the definition of $\shc{h}{r}{}(\unit{y})$ in
\eqref{Eq:window_r} with mapping $(p,q)\leftrightarrow r$, we obtain
%
\begin{align}\label{eq:result1}
\shc{h}{r}{}(\unit{y}) &= \sqrt{\frac{4\pi}{2p+1}} \shc{h}{p}{0}
\intsph \conj{Y_p^q(\unit{y})} ds(\unit{y}) \nonumber \\
&= \frac{4\pi}{\sqrt2{p+1}} \shc{h}{p}{0} \delta_{p,0} \delta_{q,0}
\nonumber \\ &= 4\pi\, \shc{h}{0}{0} \delta_{r,0}.
\end{align}

%
\noindent Using~(\ref{eq:result1}), all the summation terms
in~(\ref{Eq:kernel_integral}) become zero except for $r=0$. From the
orthonormal property of spherical harmonics, $ T(0;r;n) =
\delta_{r,n}/\sqrt{4 \pi}$. Incorporating these results
in~(\ref{Eq:kernel_integral}), we get
%
\begin{align}\label{Eq:kernel_int_element}
\intsph\psi_{n,u}(\unit{y})\,ds(\unit{y}) = \sqrt{4\pi}
\shc{h}{0}{0}\, \delta_{n,u}.
\end{align}
Substituting~(\ref{Eq:kernel_int_element}) in integrating the
elements of $\bv{\Psi}(\unit{x})$ in~(\ref{Eq:invstart}), we
obtain~(\ref{Eq:invthm}).
\end{proof}
%

% \setcounter{remark}{0}

\begin{remark}
From Theorem~\ref{thm:inversion}, we can see that we
only need to know the DC-component of the window function in order
to recover the signal exactly from its SLSHT distribution.
\end{remark}


\section{Complementary
Distribution}\label{sec:inversion_complementary}

In this section, we present the distribution transform operation
that metamorphoses the proposed SLSHT distribution in
\eqref{Eq:stft_matrix_def} into a new type of distribution which we
call its complementary distribution. We present a method to transform
the SLSHT distribution into the complementary distribution using the
definition inspired by the characteristic function in
\eqref{Eq:Ch_tf_def} in time-frequency analysis. As our proposed
SLSHT distribution in~\eqref{Eq:stft_matrix_def} is not quadratic in
nature, we use the proposed SLSHT distribution itself instead of its
squared magnitude. We will show that the complementary distribution
exhibits some desired properties as it reveals information about
both the signal and window function.  Here, we present the
mathematical definition of complementary distribution and formulate
a relation to express the complementary distribution in terms of the
signal and the window function. We also develop a matrix formulation
for the complementary distribution.
%%%%%----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

\subsection{Complementary Distribution Transformation}
In analogy with \eqref{Eq:Ch_tf_def}, the sought distribution
transform transforms the spatial domain component to a corresponding
spectral domain component and the spectral domain component to a spatial
domain component.
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%begin definition%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\begin{definition}[Spatio-spectral Complementary Distribution]
We define the spatio-spectral complementary distribution
$\bv{\kappa}(\unit{x})$ as:
%
\begin{align}\label{Eq:Ch_def}
\bv{\kappa}(\unit{x}) = \big(\,\kappa(0, {\unit{x}}), \, \kappa(1,
{\unit{x}}), \, \kappa(2, {\unit{x}}), \, \cdots, \, \kappa(N_h,
{\unit{x}})\,\big)',
\end{align}
%
where each element $\kappa(c, {\unit{x}})$ of the complementary
distribution is related to the components of SLSHT distribution
$\bv{g}(\unit{x})$ in \eqref{Eq:stft_matrix_def} by
%
\begin{align}\label{Eq:Ch_element_def}
 \kappa(c, {\unit{x}})
\triangleq \sum_{n=0}^{N_g} Y_n({\unit{x}}) \intsph
g(\unit{y},n)\overline{Y_c(\unit{y})}\,ds(\unit{y}).
\end{align}
\end{definition}
%%%%%%%end definition%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

\begin{remark}
By comparing \eqref{Eq:Ch_element_def} with \eqref{Eq:f_expansion},
we note that $\kappa(c, {\unit{x}})$ is a band-limited function on
the sphere with band-limit $L_g = L_f+L_h$.
\end{remark}

Using the expansion of $g(\unit{y},n)$ in \eqref{Eq:stft_spectral}
and matrix formulation in \eqref{Eq:stft_matrix}, the complementary
distribution can be expressed in matrix form as

\begin{align}\label{Eq:Ch_matrix_form}
\mathbf{\kappa}(\unit{x}) = \mathbf{\Upsilon}(\unit{x})\bv{f},
\end{align}
%
where $\mathbf{\Upsilon}(\unit{x})$ is a matrix of size
$(N_h+1)\times(N_f+1)$ that transforms the signal into its
complementary distribution and the entries of the matrix
$\mathbf{\Upsilon}(\unit{x})$ are given by
%
\begin{align}\label{Eq:Ch_kernel_element}
{\Upsilon_{u,c}}(\unit{x}) = (-1)^b \sqrt{\frac{4\pi}{2a+1}}
\shc{h}{a}{0} \sum_{n=0}^{N_g} Y_n(\unit{x})\,T(s,t;a,-b;\ell,m)
\end{align}
with mappings $(r,s)\leftrightarrow u$, $(a,b)\leftrightarrow c$ and
$(\ell,m)\leftrightarrow n$. The matrix formulation in
\eqref{Eq:Ch_matrix_form} transforms the signal directly into its
complementary distribution and $\mathbf{\Upsilon}(\unit{x})$ acts as
the transformation matrix for this distribution transform operation.

\subsection{Spherical Harmonics Marginal of Complementary Distribution}

We present the spherical harmonics marginal of complementary
distribution in the form of the following Theorem.

\begin{theorem}[Spherical Harmonics Marginal of Complementary
Distribution]
%\mathbf{(Spherical Harmonics Marginal of Complementary
%Distribution)}
\label{thm:cmpthm} If $\mathbf{\kappa}$ represents the complementary
distribution of the signal $f$ as defined in \eqref{Eq:Ch_def} using
azimuthally symmetric window function $h$, then the spherical
harmonics marginal of $\mathbf{\kappa}$ is obtained by integrating
the distribution over the spatial domain and is given by
%
\begin{align}\label{Eq:window_inversion}
\intsph \mathbf{\kappa}(\unit{x}) \, ds(\unit{x}) &= \big(\,[hf]_0,
\, [hf]_1, \, \cdots, \, [hf]_{N_h})',
\end{align}
%
where
\begin{align}\label{Eq:window_inversion_element}
[hf]_c = \frac{1}{\sqrt{4\pi(2a+1)}} \; \shc{h}{a}{0} \;
\shc{f}{a}{b}
\end{align}
with $(a,b)\leftrightarrow c$.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
We obtain the spherical harmonics marginal of the distribution
$\mathbf{\kappa}$ by integrating \eqref{Eq:Ch_matrix_form} over
the spatial domain
%
\begin{align}\label{Eq:Ch_iversion_start}
\intsph\mathbf{\kappa}(\unit{x}) \, d\unit{x} =
\big(\intsph\mathbf{\Upsilon}(\unit{x}) \, ds(\unit{x}) \big)\bv{f}.
\end{align}
%
The integral of kernel matrix $\mathbf{\Upsilon}(\unit{x}) $ is
obtained by integrating each matrix element. Using the definition of
$\Upsilon_{u,c}(\unit{x})$ in~(\ref{Eq:Ch_kernel_element}), we can
write
%
\begin{align}\label{Eq:Ch_kernel_integral}
\intsph {\Upsilon_{u,c}}(\unit{x}) \, ds(\unit{x}) = (-1)^b
\sqrt{\frac{4\pi}{2a+1}} \shc{h}{a}{0} \sum_{n=0}^{N_g}
 T(s,t;a,-b;\ell,m)\, \intsph Y_n(\unit{x}) ds(\unit{x}).
\end{align}
%
As a consequence of the integration over the
whole sphere, all the summation terms
in~(\ref{Eq:Ch_kernel_integral}) become zero except for $n=0$, which
implies $\ell=0$ and $m=0$. In addition, using the orthonormal
property of spherical harmonics and the definition of the spherical
harmonics triple product in \eqref{Ch4:Eq:triple_prod_abc}, we have
%
\begin{align}
T(s,t;a,-b;0,0) = \frac{(-1)^{b} \delta_{s,a} \delta_{t,b}}{\sqrt{4
\pi}},
\end{align}
%
with $(a,b)\leftrightarrow c$ and $(r,s)\leftrightarrow t$.
Incorporating these results in~(\ref{Eq:Ch_kernel_integral}), we get
%
\begin{align}\label{Eq:Ch_kernel_int_element}
\intsph {\Upsilon_{u,c}}(\unit{x}) \, ds(\unit{x})
 = \frac{ \shc{h}{a}{0}}{\sqrt{4\pi(2a+1)}}  \delta_{s,a}
 \delta_{t,b}.
\end{align}
%
Upon substituting~(\ref{Eq:Ch_kernel_int_element}) for
matrix elements of $\mathbf{\Upsilon}$ in~(\ref{Eq:Ch_iversion_start}),
we obtain the result~(\ref{Eq:window_inversion}) stated in
Theorem~\ref{thm:cmpthm}.
\end{proof}

\begin{remark}
The result in Theorem~\ref{thm:cmpthm} states that
the spherical harmonics marginal of complementary distribution gives
the element-wise product of spherical harmonic coefficients of the
signal $f$ and window function $h$ with a scaling factor that
depends upon the degree of the spherical harmonic coefficients.
Using this property of complementary
distribution~\eqref{Eq:window_inversion}, we can recover the window
function completely from its distribution assuming we obtain the
signal first from its SLSHT distribution $\bv{g}(\unit{x})$. In
conclusion, all we need is the DC-component of the window function
$\shc{h}{0}{0}$ to recover both the signal and window function from
its proposed SLSHT distribution or complementary distribution. Note
that the window function cannot be directly recovered from the SLSHT
distribution.
\end{remark}

\section{Optimal Spatio-spectral Concentration of Window Function}\label{ch4:sec:window}

The SLSHT distribution does not depend solely on the signal because
the distribution entangles the signal and the window. The
effectiveness of SLSHT distribution to reveal the information about the localized spectral contents of a signal in the spatio-spectral domain depends on the chosen window
function. If we require higher resolution in one domain, the
window should be narrower in that domain. From the uncertainty
principle on the unit sphere, a signal cannot be locally
concentrated in both the spatial and spectral
domains~\cite{Narcowich:1996}. If a window is chosen to obtain the
desired resolution in one domain, it is said to be an optimal window
if it is also optimally localized in the other
domain~\cite{Cohen:1989}.

We study the window functions jointly in both spatial and spectral
domains using the definition of uncertainty principle on the unit
sphere. The following inequality, referred as the uncertainty principle,
holds for unit energy azimuthally symmetric functions defined on the
unit sphere~\cite{Narcowich:1996,Freeden:1999}
%
\begin{align}\label{Eq:uncertain_prod1}
\frac{\sigma_{\textrm{S}}}{\sqrt{1-\sigma_{\textrm{S}}^2}}\cdot
\sigma_{\textrm{L}} \geq 1,
\end{align}

\noindent where $\sigma_{\textrm{S}}$ and $\sigma_{\textrm{L}}$
denote the variance of the window function in the spatial domain and
spectral domain respectively and are defined
as~\cite{Wieczorek:2005,Narcowich:1996}
%
\begin{align}\label{Eq:sigmaz}
\sigma_{\textrm{S}}^2 = 1 - \Big(\pi \int_0^{\pi} \sin (2\theta)\,
\big|h(\theta)\big|^2\,d\theta \,\Big)^2, \quad
\sigma_{\textrm{L}}^2 = \sum_{\ell=0}^\infty \ell (\ell+1)
|\shc{h}{\ell}{0}|^2.
\end{align}
%
\noindent Note that a unit energy window function is assumed in
\eqref{Eq:sigmaz}, which ensures that $0 \leq \sigma_{\textrm{S}}
\leq 1$.
%
