In this work, we consider and compare the following unit energy
normalized azimuthally symmetric window functions: rectangular
window, triangular window, cosine window, Hamming window, Hanning
window, the window of Simons~\textit{et al.}~\cite{Simons:1997},
Gaussian window and the \emph{eigenfunction window}, all of which
are parameterized by $\theta_c$ denoting the window truncation
width. The first five windows are defined in \cite{Harris:1978}. The
window in~\cite{Simons:1997} is obtained by truncating the
rectangular window in the spectral domain within the main spectral
lobe. The Gaussian window is a unit energy normalized function that
decays exponentially with the square of the colatitude and its
variance is chosen such that $99\%$ of the energy lies within the
truncation width. The eigenfunction window $h(\unit{x})$ arises as a
solution of a Slepian concentration problem on the
sphere~\cite{Simons:2006}. To maximize the spatial concentration of
a band-limited signal $h(\unit{x})$ with maximum spherical harmonic
degree $L_h$, equivalently represented by the column vector $\bv{h}^0$
containing the entries $\shc{h}{\ell}{0}$ for $0\leq\ell\leq L_h$,
within a polar cap region $R$ characterized by truncation width
$\theta_c$, one needs to maximize the spatial concentration
ratio~\cite{Wieczorek:2005,Simons:2006}
%
\begin{align}\label{eq:eig_value}
\lambda =\frac{\int_R |h(\unit{x})|^2\,d\unit{x} }{\intsph
|h(\unit{x})|^2\,d\unit{x}}.
\end{align}
The solution that maximizes \eqref{eq:eig_value} gives rise to the
standard eigenvalue problem $\mathbf{D}\bv{h}^0=\lambda\bv{h}^0$,
which can be solved numerically. As we are considering an azimuthally
symmetric region $R$, $\bv{h}^0 =
[\shc{h}{0}{0},\,\shc{h}{1}{0},\,\hdots,\,\shc{h}{L_h}{0}]$ denotes
the spectral response of $h(\unit{y})$ and $\mathbf{D}$ is the
($L_h+1) \times (L_h+1$) real and symmetric matrix where the entries
are given by $D_{{\ell}{\ell}'}
=\int_RY_{\ell}^0(\unit{x})Y_{{\ell}'}^{0}(\unit{x})\,d\unit{x}$. We
use the band-limited eigenfunction as window function, the one corresponding to the largest eigenvalue and having minimum possible bandwidth $L_h$ is related
to truncation width $\theta_c$ as $L_h = ({2\pi}/{\theta_c})
-1$~\cite{Simons:2006}.

\figref{ch4:fig: one} plots the (a) variance $\sigma_{\textrm{S}}$
in spatial domain, (b) variance $\sigma_{\textrm{L}}$ in spectral
domain and (c) uncertainty product in~\eqref{Eq:uncertain_prod1} for
different types of azimuthally symmetric window functions and
different values of truncation width $\pi/32\leq \theta_c\leq
\pi/4$. \figref{ch4:fig: one}(a) and \figref{ch4:fig: one}(b) show
that generally the variance in spatial domain increases with
truncation width and the variance in spectral domain decreases with
the truncation width. The rectangular window has the poorest
localization because the discontinuity at truncation points
increases its variance in the spectral domain. As expected, the
window in~\cite{Simons:1997} performs very well in the spectral
domain, but poorly in the spatial domain. The figure also shows
that the Gaussian window and the eigenfunction window exhibit better
localization behavior. Comparatively, these two windows have the
lowest variances in both domains. Note that the smaller value for
variance indicates better localization. \figref{ch4:fig: one}(c)
confirms that both the eigenfunction window and the Gaussian window
nearly attain the lower bound of $1$ for the uncertainty product of
\eqref{Eq:uncertain_prod1}. The rectangular window has the largest
uncertainty product as expected. The product for other windows,
including the window in~\cite{Simons:1997}, lie between these two
extremes.

The optimal truncation width depends on the required resolution in
both the spatial and spectral domains. As indicated in the variance
plot in \figref{ch4:fig: one}, the spatial variance
$\sigma_{\textrm{S}}$ of the eigenfunction window is very close to that
of the Gaussian window. But the spectral variance $\sigma_{\textrm{L}}$
of the eigenfunction window is lower than that of the Gaussian window,
especially at lower truncation widths. The Gaussian window and
eigenfunction window are plotted for truncation width $\theta_c =
\pi/6$ in both spatial and spectral domains in
\figref{fig:win_gauss_eig}. Both windows are normalized to unit
energy and chosen such that $99\%$ of energy lies within the
truncation width. It is observed that the eigenfunction window has
smaller bandwidth and its energy is more uniformly distributed
relative to Gaussian window in the spatial domain. Thus, the eigenfunction window can be a
good choice for window function in the SLSHT distribution.

It must be noted that compared to space-scale techniques, the
spectral-space resolution of the SLSHT is fixed for all spectral
components and spatial positions. Incorporating multi-resolution
capability in SLSHT is possible, but would require using different
bandwidth window functions for different SLSHT distribution
components, consideration of which is beyond the scope of this
correspondence. Finally, we remark that with appropriate
modifications it is possible to incorporate non-azimuthally
symmetric windows into our formulation.

