\section{Concentration Uncertainty Principle}\label{sec:principle}
In the previous section, we analyzed different window functions
from the perspective of the classic uncertainty principle that relates
the variances of the signal in the spatial and spectral
domains~\cite{Narcowich:1996,Freeden:1999,Wieczorek:2005}. A more
general notion of uncertainty, herein referred to as a concentration
uncertainty principle, was provided by Donoho and Stark. It holds that a
function and its Fourier transform cannot be simultaneously  concentrated on
any set of small measure~\cite{Donoho:1989}. The authors
in~\cite{Donoho:1989} defined two criteria for measuring
concentrations as the integral of an absolute value of the signal ($L_1$-norm) and
as the signal energy ($L_2$-norm). We note that concentration
uncertainty principles have also been extensively applied in
problems of signal reconstruction and recovery~\cite{Donoho:1989},
signal extrapolation~\cite{Candes:2006} and compressive
sampling~\cite{Goyal:2008}.

In this section, we formulate concentration uncertainty
principles for signals on the sphere where the concentration is
measured using the $L_1$-norm and $L_2$-norm of a signal
respectively. More precisely, if the signal $f(\unit{x})$ on the
sphere is concentrated on some spatial region $R\subset \sphh$ and
also concentrated on some spectral region $N = [N_1,N_2]$ which
denotes the spherical harmonic coefficients $\shc{f}{\ell}{m}$ with
$N_1 \leq \ell \leq N_2$ and $-\ell \leq m \leq \ell$, we develop
the principles which relate the concentration measures and
concentration regions in both spatial and spectral domains. Note
that the region $R$ does not need to be connected, whereas for the
sake of simplicity, we consider the connected interval $N$ in
spectral domain but this can also be generalized for
non-connected intervals. Here connected interval means that $N=[N_1,N_2]$ contains all degrees between $N_1$ and $N_2$. We first define the selection operators in
both spatial and spectral domains which select the part of a signal
in a selected spatial or spectral region~\cite{Rod_icspcs:2008}.
Then we state and prove the uncertainty principles. We first define
$L_p$ norm of a signal defined on the sphere and the $L_p$ norm of
an operator on $\lsph$. Later, we formulate selection operators in
the spatial and spectral domain and then we provide the
concentration uncertainty principles.

\subsection{$L_p$ norm of Signal and Operator}
For a signal $f\in \lsph$, its $L_p$-norm is defined
as~\cite{Schechter:2002}
\begin{align}\label{Eq:p_norm_signal_def}
\|f\|_p = \big(\intsph |f(\unit{x})|^p\, ds(\unit{x})\big)^{1/p}.
\end{align}
%
Define an operator $\mathcal{K}$ for signals on the sphere using
general Fredholm integral equation~\cite{kennedy:book}
\begin{align}\label{Eq:gen_operator_def}
(\mathcal{K}f)(\unit{x})\,=\,\intsph K(\unit{x},
\unit{y})\,f(\unit{y})ds(\unit{y}),
\end{align}
where $K(\unit{x}, \unit{y})$ is the kernel for an operator
$\mathcal{K}$. Since it is important in the sequel, we define the
$L_p$-norm of an operator $\mathcal{K}$ as
\begin{align}\label{Eq:Lp_norm_operator}
\|\mathcal{K}\|_p = \sup_{f\in
\sphh}\frac{\|\mathcal{K}f\|_p}{\|f\|_p}.
\end{align}
Also, the Hilbert-Schmidt norm of an operator $\mathcal{K}$ with
kernel $K({\unit{x},\unit{y}})$ is given by~\cite{Donoho:1989}
\begin{align}\label{Eq:HS_norm_operator}
\|\mathcal{K}\|_H = \left(\intsph \intsph |K(\unit{x},\unit{y})|^2
ds(\unit{x}) \,ds(\unit{y})\right)^{1/2},
\end{align}
\noindent which is a bound on $\|\mathcal{K}\|_2$. We note that the kernel $K({\unit{x},\unit{y}})$ will always be taken as Hilbert-Schmidt, meaning $\|\mathcal{K}\|_H <\infty$, which is a sufficient condition to make the integral operator compact.



\subsection{Selection Operators on the Sphere}

\begin{definition}[Spatial Selection Operator] \emph{Define the spatial selection
operator $\mathcal{K}_R$ which selects the function in a region $R$
with kernel $K_R(\unit{x}, \unit{y})$ as
\begin{align}\label{Eq:kernel_spatial_def}
K_R(\unit{x}, \unit{y}) \,\triangleq \, I_R(\unit{x})
\delta(\unit{x}, \unit{y}),
\end{align}
where $I_R(\unit{x})=1$ for $\unit{x}\in R\subset \sphh$ and
$I_R(\unit{x})=0$ for $\unit{x}\in \sphh \backslash R$ is an
indicator function of the region $R$ and $\delta(\unit{x},
\unit{y})$ denotes the Dirac delta function on the sphere given in
\eqref{Eq:delta_def_expansion} .}
\end{definition}

\begin{definition}[Spectral Selection Operator] \emph{Define the spectral selection
operator $\mathcal{K}_N$ with $N = [N_1,N_2]$, which selects the
contribution of spherical harmonics in spectral region $N$ in a
signal and has the kernel $K_N$ as
\begin{align}\label{Eq:kernel_spectral_def}
K_N(\unit{x}, \unit{y}) \,\triangleq \,
\sum_{\ell=N_1}^{N_2}\,\sum_{m=-\ell}^\ell\, Y_\ell^m(\unit{x})\,
\overline{Y_\ell^m(\unit{y})}.
\end{align}}
\end{definition}
We note that both the spatial and spectral selection operators are
idempotent and self-adjoint. That is, they are projection
operators.

\subsection{The $L_1$-norm Uncertainty Principle}
We first present the $L_1$-norm uncertainty principle which relates
the concentration of signal in spatial and spectral domains to the
measure of spatial and spectral regions, where the concentration is
determined using the $L_1$-norm of a signal. We say that $f$ is
$\epsilon_R$ concentrated in the spatial domain and $\epsilon_N$
concentrated in the spectral domain if $\|f-\mathcal{K}_Rf\|_1 \leq
\epsilon_R$ and $\|f-\mathcal{K}_Nf\|_1 \leq \epsilon_N$
respectively.
%
\begin{theorem}[$L_1$-norm Uncertainty Principle]
\emph{If the unit $L_1$-norm signal $f$ is $\epsilon_R$ concentrated
in the region $R\subset\sphh$ and $\epsilon_N$ concentrated in the
spectral region $N=[N_1,N_2]$, then
\begin{align}\label{Eq:thm1_statement}
\frac{A}{4\pi}\,{\Big((N_2+1)^2 -N_1^2}\Big) \,\geq\,
\frac{1-\epsilon_R - \epsilon_N}{1+\epsilon_N},
\end{align}
where $A = \intsph I_R(\unit{x})ds(\unit{x})$ denotes the area of
the region $R$. }\end{theorem}
\begin{proof}
Since, the signal $f$ is unit-norm, we have
\begin{align}\label{Eq:proof_thm1_1}
\|f\|_1 = \intsph|f(\unit{x})| ds(\unit{x}) = 1
\end{align}
and using the given $\|f-\mathcal{K}_Rf\|_1 \leq \epsilon_R$ and
$\|f-\mathcal{K}_Nf\|_1 \leq \epsilon_N$ and the fact that
$\|f-\mathcal{K}_Rf\|_1\geq \|f\|_1-\|\mathcal{K}_Rf\|_1$, we obtain
\begin{align}\label{Eq:proof_thm1_2}
\|\mathcal{K}_Rf\|_1 + \epsilon_R \geq 1\,,\quad \|\mathcal{K}_Nf\|
+ \epsilon_N \geq 1.
\end{align}
Define a composite operator $\mathcal{K}_{RN} =
\mathcal{K}_{R}\mathcal{K}_{N}$. From \eqref{Eq:proof_thm1_1} and
\eqref{Eq:proof_thm1_2}, we obtain the $L_1$-norm of this composite
operator as
\begin{align}\label{Eq:proof_thm1_3}
\|\mathcal{K}_{RN}\|_1 \geq \|\mathcal{K}_{RN}f\|_1 \geq 1
-\epsilon_R-\epsilon_N.
\end{align}
%
\noindent Since, the operator $\mathcal{K}_N$ is idempotent, using
the spherical harmonic expansion of $f$, we can write
%
\begin{align}\label{Eq:proof_thm1_4}
(\mathcal{K}_Nf)(\unit{x}) &=
\sum_{\ell=N_1}^{N_2}\,\sum_{m=-\ell}^\ell\,\intsph
Y_\ell^m(\unit{x})\, \overline{Y_\ell^m(\unit{y})}
(\mathcal{K}_Nf)(\unit{y})\,ds(\unit{y}).
\end{align}

\noindent Using the spherical harmonics addition theorem in
\eqref{Eq:addition_theorem}, we can obtain from
\eqref{Eq:proof_thm1_4} that
%
\begin{align}\label{Eq:proof_thm1_44}
|(\mathcal{K}_Nf)(\unit{x})| &=
\sum_{\ell=N_1}^{N_2}\frac{2\ell+1}{4\pi}\intsph |P_\ell^0(\unit{x}
\cdot \unit{y})| ds(\unit{y})
\end{align}

\noindent and we have $\sup\|P_\ell^0(\unit{x} \cdot \unit{y})\|_1 =
1$ and $\|(\mathcal{K}_Nf)\|_\infty =
\max|(\mathcal{K}_Nf)(\unit{x})| $ for $\unit{x}\in\sphh$, which
implies
\begin{align}\label{Eq:proof_thm1_5}
\|(\mathcal{K}_Nf)\|_\infty \, \leq\, \frac{1}{4\pi}\Big((N_2+1)^2
-N_1^2\Big) \|(\mathcal{K}_Nf)\|_1.
\end{align}
For the composite operator $\mathcal{K}_{RN}$, we have
\begin{align}\label{Eq:proof_thm1_6}
\|\mathcal{K}_{RN}f\|_1 =
\int_{R}|(\mathcal{K}_Nf)(\unit{x})|ds(\unit{x}) \leq
\|\mathcal{K}_Nf\|_\infty A,
\end{align}
where $A$ is the area of the region $R$. Using
\eqref{Eq:proof_thm1_6} and \eqref{Eq:proof_thm1_5}, we obtain
\begin{align}\label{Eq:proof_thm1_7}
\|\mathcal{K}_{RN}f\|_1\, \leq\, \frac{A}{4\pi}\,\Big((N_2+1)^2
-N_1^2\Big) \|(\mathcal{K}_Nf)\|_1.
\end{align}
Combining \eqref{Eq:proof_thm1_1}, \eqref{Eq:proof_thm1_2} and
\eqref{Eq:proof_thm1_3} with \eqref{Eq:proof_thm1_7} gives the
stated result.
\end{proof}
\begin{remark}
\emph{The factor $\frac{A}{4\pi}\,{\Big((N_2+1)^2 -N_1^2}\Big)$ on
the left hand side of \eqref{Eq:thm1_statement} can be defined as a
generalized space-bandwidth product, with the term $A/4\pi$ being a
measure of the spatial region ${R}$ and the term $(N_2+1)^2 -N_1^2$
being a measure of the spectral region $N=[N_1,N_2]$. For $N_1=0$, this
space-bandwidth product is referred to as an equivalent of the
Shannon number in~\cite{Simons:2006} for signals defined on the
sphere.}
\end{remark}
%

\subsection{The $L_2$-norm Uncertainty Principle}
Next, we present the uncertainty principle for the case in which the
concentration is measured using $L_2$-norm, which is a measure of
energy of the signal and makes this principle more appealing and
practical.
%
\begin{theorem}[$L_2$-norm Uncertainty Principle]
\emph{If the unit $L_2$-norm signal $f$ is $\epsilon_R$ concentrated
in the region $R\subset\sphh$ such that $\|f-\mathcal{K}_Rf\|_2 \leq
\epsilon_R$ and $\epsilon_N$ concentrated in the spectral region
$N=[N_1,N_2]$ such that $\|f-\mathcal{K}_Nf\|_2 \leq \epsilon_N$,
then
\begin{align}\label{Eq:thm2_statement}
\frac{A}{4\pi}\,{\Big((N_2+1)^2 -N_1^2}\Big) \,\geq\, ({1-\epsilon_R
- \epsilon_N})^2,
\end{align}
where $A = \intsph I_R(\unit{x})d\unit{x}$ denotes the area of the
region $R$. }\end{theorem}
\begin{proof}
By definition, $\|f\|_2=1$, $\|f-\mathcal{K}_Rf\|_2 \leq \epsilon_R$
and $\|f-\mathcal{K}_Nf\|_2 \leq \epsilon_N$, which implies
\begin{align}\label{Eq:proof_thm2_1}
\|\mathcal{K}_Rf\|_2\geq1-\epsilon_R\,,\quad
\|\mathcal{K}_Nf\|_2\geq1-\epsilon_N.
\end{align}
Define a composite operator $\mathcal{K}_{NR} =
\mathcal{K}_{N}\mathcal{K}_{R}$ composed of spatial selection
operation $\mathcal{R}$ followed by spectral selection
$\mathcal{K}_N$. By substituting \eqref{Eq:kernel_spatial_def} and
\eqref{Eq:kernel_spectral_def} in \eqref{Eq:gen_operator_def} and
using the representation of Dirac delta in
\eqref{Eq:delta_def_expansion}, we obtain the kernel
$K_{NR}(\unit{x}, \unit{y})$ as
\begin{align}\label{Eq:proof_thm2_2}
{K}_{NR}(\unit{x}, \unit{y}) &=
\sum_{\ell=N_1}^{N_2}\,\sum_{m=-\ell}^\ell\, Y_\ell^m(\unit{x})\,
\overline{Y_\ell^m(\unit{y})} I_R(\unit{y}).
\end{align}

\noindent The Hilbert-Schmidt norm of the composite operator
$\mathcal{K}_{NR}$ can be obtained using \eqref{Eq:HS_norm_operator}
along with the spherical harmonics addition theorem in
\eqref{Eq:addition_theorem} and the fact that $P_\ell^0(1)=1$ as
\begin{align}\label{Eq:proof_thm2_3}
\|\mathcal{K}_{NR}\|_H &=
\Bigg(\sum_{\ell=N_1}^{N_2}\frac{2\ell+1}{4\pi} \int_{R}ds(\unit{x})
\nonumber \Bigg)^{1/2}\\ &= \Bigg(\frac{A}{4\pi}\,{\big((N_2+1)^2
-N_1^2}\big)\Bigg)^{1/2}.
\end{align}
Now, the effect of the composite operator on the concentration can
be readily obtained from \eqref{Eq:proof_thm2_1} as
\begin{align}\label{Eq:proof_thm2_4}
\|\mathcal{K}_{NR}\,f\|_2 \geq 1 - \epsilon_R -\epsilon_N.
\end{align}
Using definition of the norm of operator in
\eqref{Eq:Lp_norm_operator},
$\|\mathcal{K}_{NR}\|_2\geq\|\mathcal{K}_{NR}\,f\|_2$ and the fact
that $\|\mathcal{K}_{NR}\|_H\geq\|\mathcal{K}_{NR}\|_2$ and combined
with \eqref{Eq:proof_thm2_3} and \eqref{Eq:proof_thm2_4} gives the
result in \eqref{Eq:thm2_statement}.
\end{proof}

\begin{remark}
\emph{We can infer from the proof of Theorem~$4.4$ that the
composite operator $\mathcal{K}_{RN} =
\mathcal{K}_{R}\mathcal{K}_{N}$ is an adjoint of the operator
$\mathcal{K}_{NR}$ which implies that the Hilbert-Schmidt norm of
these two composite operators is equal and given by
\eqref{Eq:proof_thm2_3}.}
\end{remark}


\subsection{Sharpness of the Uncertainty Principle Bound}
We provide an analysis of the bound imposed by the $L_2$-norm
uncertainty principle on simultaneous spatial and spectral
signal concentration. We
compare this bound with the largest eigenvalue obtained from the
Slepian concentration problem for azimuthally symmetric signals on
the sphere proposed in
\cite{Albertella:1999,Wieczorek:2005,Simons:2006}. First, we
consider the spatial polar cap regions $R$ characterized by central
angle $\Theta$ with area $A = \int_o^\pi\int_0^\Theta\sin\theta
d\theta d\phi = 2\pi(1-\cos\Theta)$ and the spectral regions
$N=[0,N_2]$. We use $\lambda_c(\Theta,N_2)$ to denote the largest
eigenvalue obtained numerically by solving the concentration problem
on the sphere~\cite{Wieczorek:2005}, which finds the band-limited
signal of maximum spectral degree $N_2$ with maximum energy
concentration in the polar cap region of angle $\Theta$. We obtain
a simplified form of the product on the left hand side in
\eqref{Eq:thm2_statement} for spatial and spectral regions under
consideration as $\lambda_0(\Theta,N_2) = (N_2+1)^2(1-\cos\Theta)/2
$, which serves as an uncertainty bound. Fig~\ref{fig:uncertain1}
shows the comparison of $\lambda_c(\Theta,N_2)$ and
$\lambda_0(\Theta,N_2)$ against $\Theta$ for $N_2 = 10$ and $N_2 =
20$, which suggests that $\lambda_0$ serves as a sharp bound for
the spatial polar cap region $R$ and it gets tighter for smaller
values of $\lambda_0$.

